## <summary>
## SELinux policy module for demo-03-svc.
##
## Grants the standard container_t SELinux type the additional
## io_uring permission class needed to run io_uring-based servers
## inside an otherwise-unmodified container security context.
##
## Without this module installed, container_t cannot create io_uring
## instances on Fedora/RHEL 9+ — io_uring_setup returns -EACCES from
## the kernel SELinux LSM hook (not from seccomp; SELinux denial is
## a separate gate).
##
## Loading:
##   make -f /usr/share/selinux/devel/Makefile demo03_iouring.pp
##   sudo semodule -i demo03_iouring.pp
##
## Verifying:
##   sudo semodule -l | grep demo03_iouring
##   sudo seinfo -c io_uring
##
## Unloading:
##   sudo semodule -r demo03_iouring
##
## Threat model: this module ONLY adds io_uring access. It does not
## relax any other container_t restriction. Compared to label=disable
## (which substitutes spc_t for container_t), this is a surgical
## permission grant that preserves all other MAC enforcement.
## </summary>

policy_module(demo03_iouring, 1.0)

require {
    type container_t;
    class io_uring { create override_creds sqpoll };
}

########################################
## io_uring access for container_t.
##
## Permissions explained (see io_uring(7) and the SELinux policy
## reference for the io_uring class introduced in policy v33):
##
##   create:           required to call io_uring_setup(2)
##   override_creds:   required for IORING_OP_OPENAT2 and similar ops
##                     that act with the credentials of the ring creator
##                     rather than the issuing thread. Demo doesn't use
##                     these ops, but Asio's io_uring backend may register
##                     creds on init — granting it is defense-in-depth
##                     for Asio.
##   sqpoll:           required if a ring is registered with IORING_SETUP_SQPOLL
##                     to spawn a kernel thread that polls SQEs. Our demo
##                     uses default mode (no SQPOLL), so this isn't strictly
##                     required — but the cost is zero and the symmetry
##                     with override_creds keeps the policy simpler.
##
## The actual io_uring ring permissions (IORING_OP_* control) are
## enforced by the kernel beyond SELinux — registering an op like
## IORING_REGISTER_BUFFERS still requires CAP_SYS_NICE, which our
## container drops via cap_drop: ALL. SELinux grants the ability to
## use the io_uring interface; the kernel decides what operations
## that interface can actually perform.
########################################

allow container_t self:io_uring { create override_creds sqpoll };
